</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">N<sup>o</sup> 4</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">placed upon high Stages.  The envelops being decayed generally exposed the contents.  We now met with a Mandane armed.  He took us by the hand and desired us to put up at the Village.  We then observed Women and children hoeing in the fields.  At the entrance of the Village we were met by the Chief called the Black Cat attended by many of his tribe with whom we had to shake hands.  The Chief immediately conducted us to one of his tents which was appropriated to Strangers where one of his wives attended.  In a moment the whole village flocked round us<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> anxious to See the articles we had brought for Trade.  After our things were taken in &#8212; The Chief gave our Horses is charge to a young man and told us not to be uneasy about them as good care would be taken of them.  In the hut we found Buffaloe hides spread as seats for our reception.  Soon after we were presented with two large dishes of boiled Corn and beans as well as a large dish of dried meat &#8212; which few of us could eat but which the natives prefered to any other as they seldom make use of meat until it begins to spoil and smell.  We were then invited to Several huts and presented at each with a similar assortment of eatables<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Soon after sundries were brought for trade.</p>
